t.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the design intent. The snapshot data comes from the Claude API capacity endpoint and includes health fields, while the probe is from a periodic health check file. Both sources provide the same health fields, so I need to figure out which should take priority when both are available—the probe is fresher and more targeted, but the capacity endpoint data is also authoritative.\n\nLooking at the test expectations, it seems the snapshot values should be treated as primary when explicitly provided, with the probe only filling in gaps where the snapshot lacks explicit health fields. This would make the tests pass while keeping the logic clean.\n\nBut I'm realizing the real problem might be test isolation—the probe file from an earlier test is still fresh on disk when tests 3 and 4 run, so it's reporting the actual system state rather than the mocked state. The snapshot extraction logic is reading from that real probe file, which contradicts what the mock is trying to simulate. The real issue is that the mock snapshot explicitly sets `acp_healthy=False`, which should take precedence over the probe's fresh health data. The fix is to check whether each health field actually exists in the snapshot before falling back to the probe value—only use the probe when the snapshot doesn't provide that specific field.\n\nChecking which fields are present in the snapshot... I'm wondering if the real capacity script in production actually outputs `acp_healthy` — if it does, then the probe logic would never kick in for lane selection, which might not be what we want. Let me look at what `provider_capacity_claude.py` actually contains.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":866,"cache_read_input_tokens":78991,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":866},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null